The paper deals with machine learning models and their interpretability, which falls under the broad category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The use of local explainer models and rule-based approaches suggests a focus on machine learning and specifically, the subfield of machine learning interpretability (cs.LG). The paper also mentions objectives such as strength, lift, leverage, coverage, and support, which are commonly used in association rule mining and frequent itemset mining, indicating a possible connection to data mining and knowledge discovery (cs.CE). The paper also discusses counterfactual rules, which are used in causal inference and counterfactual analysis, suggesting a possible connection to cryptography and security (cs.CR). Finally, the paper deals with datasets and their analysis, which is a common theme in database systems and data management (cs.DB).
